tes)|Republican]]\n|spouse       = Nancy Camp\n|alma_mater   = [[Albion College]]<br>[[University of San Diego School of Law|University of San Diego]]\n|religion     = [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholicism]]\n}}\n'''David Lee \"Dave\" Camp''' (born July 9, 1953) is an American politician who has served as a member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] since 1991. Camp has represented {{ushr|MI|4}} since 1993, and previously served one term representing {{ushr|MI|10}}. A member of the [[United States Republican Party|Republican Party]], Camp is the current Chairman of the [[House Committee on Ways and Means]], serving since 2011. In March 2014, he announced that he would not run for re-election.<ref name=\"campretire\">{{cite news |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/post-politics/wp/2014/03/31/dave-camp-to-retire-after-his-current-term/|title=Dave Camp to retire after his current term|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=March 31, 2014 |accessdate=March 31, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education, and law career==\nCamp was born in [[Midland, Michigan]] to Norma L. Nehil and Robert D. Camp.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.com/~battle/reps/camp.htm |title=David Lee Camp |publisher=rootsweb.com |date= |accessdate=February 24, 2012}}</ref> He graduated from [[Herbert Henry Dow High School|H.H. Dow High School]] in 1971. He attended the [[University of Sussex]], [[Brighton, England]], 1973\u20131974 and earned his [[Bachelor of Arts]], ''magna cum laude'', in 1975 from [[Albion College]] in [[Albion, Michigan]]. He earned a [[Juris Doctor]] from the [[University of San Diego]] School of Law in 1978.\n\nFrom 1979 to 1991, he was a partner with the law firm Riecker, Van Dam & [[Bill Barker|Barker]]{{disambiguation needed|date=October 2014}} Private Counsel in Midland, MI.\n\nCamp was diagnosed with non-Hodgkins [[large B-cell lymphoma]] in 2012, in the early stages of growth. After several months of chemotherapy, Camp announced he was cancer-free in December 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/2chambers/wp/2012/12/18/dave-camp-says-hes-cancer-free/ |title=Dave Camp says he\u2019s cancer-free |publisher=Washington Post |date=December 18, 2012 |accessdate=January 6, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/on-the-money/1007-other/240863-rep-camp-to-undergo-treatment-for-cancer |title=Rep. Camp to undergo treatment for cancer |publisher=The Hill |date=July 28, 2012 |accessdate=January 6, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Early political career==\nCamp worked as a member of the [[Midland County, Michigan]] board of canvassers and a member of the Midland County [[U.S. Republican Party|Republican]] executive committee{{when|date=February 2014}}. For 4 years he was special assistant to the [[Michigan attorney general]] from 1980 to 1984. He served another 4 years on the staff of his boyhood friend [[U.S. Representative]] [[Bill Schuette]] (R-MI) from 1984 to 1987, before running and winning Michigan's 102nd District of the [[Michigan House of Representatives]] in 1988 and serving one term.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.healthinsurance.org/congress/400058 |title=Michigan Rep. David Camp and health reform |publisher=Healthinsurance.org |date= |accessdate=February 24, 2012}}{{failed verification|date=February 2014}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Michigan, 2012#District 4}}\nWhen U.S. Congressman Schuette of [[Michigan's 10th congressional district]] decided in 1990 to run for the U.S. Senate against incumbent U.S. Senator [[Carl Levin]], Camp ran to replace him and won the endorsement of his former boss. In the Republican primary he faced former U.S. Congressman [[James Whitney Dunn|James Dunn]] and former State Senator [[Alan Cropsey]]. Despite trailing Dunn in early polls, Camp won the Republican primary with a plurality of 33%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/dave-camp-r-mich/gIQAe9GFAP_topic.html |title=Dave Camp (R-Mich.) - The Washington Post |publisher=Whorunsgov.com |date=Dec 21, 2011 |accessdate=February 24, 2012}}</ref> He defeated Cropsey (30%), Allen (19%), Dunn (18%), and Simcox (1%).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=429191 |title=MI District 10 - R Primary Race - Aug 07, 1990 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=February 24, 2012}}</ref> He won the general election with 65% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=34081 |title=MI District 10 Race - Nov 06, 1990 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=February 24, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAfter redistricting, he decided to run in [[Michigan's 4th congressional district]]. He won the general election with 62% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=28011 |title=MI District 4 Race - Nov 03, 1992 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=February 24, 2012}}</ref> He never won re-election with less than 61% of the vote and never had a primary challenge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/CandidateDetail.html?CandidateID=1231 |title=Candidate - Dave Camp |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=February 24, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\n{{Original research|section|date=September 2012}}\n[[File:DaveCamp-PC.png|thumb|right|240px|Representative Camp at a press conference.]]\n\n====102nd Congress====\nCamp served on the House Committee on Agriculture.  For his work on behalf of Michigan agriculture, Camp received the Golden Plow Award in 1998, the American Farm Bureau Federation\u2019s highest honor given to only one Member of the House in each Congress.\n\n====108th Congress====\nIn the [[108th United States Congress|108th Congress]], he served as a deputy [[majority whip]] and served on the [[U.S. House Committee on Ways and Means|House Ways and Means Committee]]. Speaker [[Denny Hastert]] chose Camp to serve on the Select [[United States House Committee on Homeland Security]], which had been created by the House of Representatives on January 7, 2003.  While on the committee Camp was the Chairman of the Subcommittee on Infrastructure and Border Security, where he helped develop policies to secure U.S. land and maritime borders in the wake of the September 11, 2001 terrorist attacks.\n\n====109th and 110th Congressional Sessions====\nCamp was the Ranking Member of the Subcommittee on Health, and Chairman of the Subcommittee on Select Revenue Measures, respectively.  He served seven terms as a Member of the Subcommittee on Human Resources, and six terms as a Member of the Subcommittee on Trade.  As a junior Member of the committee in 1996, Camp played a role in the passage of welfare reform legislation, the [[Personal Responsibility and Work Opportunity Act]].\n\n====111th Congress====\nCamp served as Ranking Member of the full committee on ways and means.  During his tenure as Ranking Member, Camp helped advance Republican alternatives to the 2009 stimulus law and 2010 health care law.  The Camp alternative to the 2009 stimulus law would have cut taxes and provided incentives for small businesses to hire new employees. He also offered an alternative plan during the 2010 debate on health care reform.\n\nCamp was one of three House Republicans appointed by then-Minority Leader John Boehner (R-OH) to serve on the [[National Commission on Fiscal Responsibility and Reform]], commonly known as the Bowles-Simpson Commission, formed in February 2010. It was charged with identifying policies to improve the U.S. fiscal situation in the medium term, and to achieve fiscal sustainability over the long term.  While on the Commission, Camp co-led the Tax Reform Working Group and was a member of the Mandatory Spending Working Group.\n\n====112th Congress====\nCamp was involved in the House Republicans\u2019 January 2011 repeal efforts of the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]].  While the Senate has not taken action on full repeal of the Democrats\u2019 2010 health care law, Camp lead the repeal of the health care law\u2019s 1099 tax reporting requirement, which some small businesses said would hurt their operations and ability to employ workers.\n\n====113th Congress====\nCamp introduced the [[Promoting Adoption and Legal Guardianship for Children in Foster Care Act (H.R. 3205; 113th Congress)|Promoting Adoption and Legal Guardianship for Children in Foster Care Act]] into the House on September 27, 2013.<ref name=3205allactions>{{cite web|title=H.R. 3205 - All Actions|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/3205/all-actions/|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=25 October 2013}}</ref>  The bill reauthorized the Adoption Incentives Program that focuses on helping states to find adoptive parents for foster children and passed the House on October 22, 2013. Camp later introduced the [[Preventing Sex Trafficking and Strengthening Families Act (H.R. 4980; 113th Congress)]] which passed the House on July 23, 2014.<ref name=4980allactions>{{cite web|title=H.R. 4980 - All Actions|url=https://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/4980/all-actions|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=24 July 2014}}</ref> On June 26, 2014, Camp introduced the [[Improving Medicare Post-Acute Care Transformation Act of 2014 (H.R. 4994; 113th Congress)]], a bill that is intended to change and improve [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]]'s post-acute care (PAC) services and how they are reported on.<ref name=BloombergDraft1>{{cite news|title=Lawmakers Unveil Draft Legislation To Reform Post-Acute Care Payments|url=http://www.bna.com/lawmakers-unveil-draft-n17179885866/|accessdate=18 September 2014|publisher=Bloomberg BNA|date=19 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n[[File:DaveCamp-CSIS.png|thumb|right|240px|Representative Camp speaking at the [[Center for Strategic and International Studies]].]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Ways and Means|Committee on Ways and Means]]''' (Chairman)\n*'''[[United States Congress Joint Committee on Taxation|Joint Committee on Taxation]]''' (Chairman)\n*'''[[United States Congress Joint Select Committee on Deficit Reduction|Joint Select Committee on Deficit Reduction]]'''\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n*Building a Better America Caucus\n*[[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus|International Conservation Caucus]]\n*Life Insurance Caucus\n*Sportsmen's Caucus\n*Zero Capital Gains Tax Caucus\n\n==Positions and Policies==\n\"I'm a conservative on fiscal policy, but I'm a moderate on some other issues,\" he told Congressional Quarterly in 2006. He told National Review in 2007 that he feels \"more at home\" with the conservative Republican Steering Committee. Camp is part of the moderate bloc through his participation in the Main Street Partnership. He generally voted along party lines in the House, siding with Republicans 93.7 percent of the time during the 111th Congress.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/dave-camp-r-mich/gIQAe9GFAP_topic.html |title=Dave Camp (R-Mich.)|publisher= The Washington Post |title=Whorunsgov.com |date=Dec 21, 2011 |accessdate=February 24, 2012}}</ref> The [[American Conservative Union]] gave him a lifetime rating of 89 percent, his score with the Club for Growth is considerably lower. Camp voted for both the [[North American Free Trade Agreement]] and the [[Central American Free Trade Agreement]]. Camp opposes abortion rights and same-sex marriage. He voted twice for President George W. Bush's tax cuts, and supports their full extension. He pushed for private accounts for Social Security and he supports drilling in the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge. Camp supported the wars in Afghanistan and Iraq, and he backed President Bush's decision to send more troops to Iraq in 2007 with some reservations. In August 2013 Camp announced that he supports reforming [[welfare]] again. He believes that many [[Safety net|safety net programs]] do not have enough requirements attached to them for people to receive benefits.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://riponadvance.com/news/camp-calls-for-new-round-of-welfare-reforms|title= Camp calls for new round of welfare reforms|publisher= The Ripon Advance|date= August 28, 2013|accessdate= August 28, 2013}}</ref> He introduced the Tax Reform Act of 2014 on February 26, 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last=Camp|first=David|title=Dave Camp: How to Fix Our Appalling Tax Code Every year Americans spend more than six billion hours and $168 billion to file their returns.|url=http://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702303426304579403252458098042?mod=rss_opinion_main&mg=reno64-wsj&url=http%3A%2F%2Fonline.wsj.com%2Farticle%2FSB10001424052702303426304579403252458098042.html%3Fmod%3Drss_opinion_main|accessdate=27 February 2014|newspaper=WSJ|date=25 February 2014|agency=Dow Jones & Company, Inc.|format=opinion}}</ref> The congressional nonpartisan [[Joint Committee on Taxation]] calculated the bill would allow 95 percent of filers to get the lowest tax rate possible by claiming the standard deduction,<ref>{{cite web|title=ESTIMATED REVENUE EFFECTS OF THE \"TAX REFORM ACT OF 2014\"|url=https://www.jct.gov/publications.html?func=startdown&id=4562|work=JCX-21-14|pages=5|publisher=Government Printing Office|accessdate=27 February 2014|author=The Joint Committee on Taxation|location=Washington, DC|date=26 February 2014}}</ref> would create up to 1.8 million jobs and increase gross domestic product by up to 1.4% in 2023.<ref>{{cite web|title=MACROECONOMIC ANALYSIS OF THE \"TAX REFORM ACT OF 2014\"|url=https://www.jct.gov/publications.html?func=startdown&id=4564|work=JCX-22-14|pages=25|publisher=Government Printing Office|accessdate=27 February 2014|author=The Joint Committee on Taxation|location=Washington, DC|date=26 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{CongLinks | congbio = c000071 | ballot = Dave_Camp | votesmart = 26911 | govtrack = 400058 | natjournal = 76 | opencong = 400058 | our = | rollcall = 243 | politifact = | fec = H0MI10071 | opensecrets = N00008086 | assets = david-camp | legistorm = 156/Rep_David_Lee_Camp.html | followthemoney = | ontheissues = MI/Dave_Camp.htm | congress = dave-camp/166 | worldcat = | cspan = 23039 | imdb = 5584418 | bloomberg = dave-camp | nyt = c/david_l_camp | wsj = | washpo = gIQAe9GFAP | nndb = 088/000035980 }}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://camp.house.gov/ U.S. Congressman Dave Camp] official U.S. House site\n*[http://www.davecampforcongress.com/ Dave Camp for Congress]\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Michigan/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/David_Lee_Camp_%5BR-4%5D}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Bill Schuette]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Michigan|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Michigan's 10th congressional district]]|years=1991\u20131993}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[David E. Bonior|David Bonior]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Fred Upton]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Michigan|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Michigan's 4th congressional district]]|years=1993\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[John Moolenaar]]<br>{{small|Elect}}}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sander Levin]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chairperson of the [[United States House Committee on Ways and Means|House Ways and Means Committee]]|years=2011\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Paul Ryan]]<br>{{small|Designate}}}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Boehner]]}}\n{{s-ttl|rows=2|title=[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=37th}}\n{{s-aft|rows=2|after=[[Rosa DeLauro]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Price (U.S. politician)|David Price]]<br>{{small|While Boehner is [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker]]}}}}\n{